  "doc_id": "32692",
  "text": "Additional studies described GLUT10 in the endomembrane system of the cell. Coucke et al. found GLUT10 protein of human fibroblasts in the perinuclear region [CITATION_1] , and Segade demonstrated that GLUT10 localized to the ER by using PAC-1 rat aortic smooth muscle cells too [CITATION_2] . Regarding the transport activity, the paper questioned GLUT10 as a bona fide glucose transporter and suggested AA to be its physiological ligand. This would be in accordance with the observed symptoms of ATS patients, such as laxity of the skin and hyperextensibility of the joints, as in ATS, the decreased DHA uptake might result in insufficient levels of available AA for the posttranslational modification of extracellular matrix proteins in the ER [CITATION_3] . Németh et al. showed that GLUT10 was indeed a DHA transporter of the ER, and DHA transport is defective through the endomembranes of ATS fibroblasts [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Its possible ER localization was also reinforced by the relatively high 39.1% of the ER prediction score of PSORTII (Table 1) .",
